<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-07-07T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-07-07T12:00:00-05:00" n="1084" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1084">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.801/7–749: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Douglas</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-07-07T18:00:00+01:00">July 7, 1949—6
                                p. m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received July 7—5:39 p. m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>2649. Canton’s Cantel 670 and 673 to Department re closure Chinese ports.
                        Scarlett, Foreign Office, states Foreign Office considering reply to latest
                        Chinese note but will require ministerial conference for approval. Also that
                        in his personal opinion it very doubtful that British Government would
                        consent convoy British merchant ships through waters closed by
                        Nationalists.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Douglas</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>